      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose we increase <m>x</m> by 1 from the point <m>(2,-1)</m>. How does the <m>y</m>-value change? What is the point on the line with <m>x</m>-coordinate <m>3</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            As we increase <m>x</m> by 1, the <m>y</m>-value increases by <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>. The point on the line with the <m>x</m>-coordinate <m>3</m> is <m>(3, -\frac{1}{3})</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            If a line has a slope of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>, this means that an increase of 3 in the <m>x</m>-direction results in increase of 2 in the <m>y</m>-direction. If we scale this to a one-unit rate of change, an increase of 1 unit in the <m>x</m>-direction results in an increase of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> in the <m>y</m>-direction. From the point <m>(2, -1)</m> to the point with an <m>x</m>-value of 3, this requires a 1 unit increase in the rate of change in the <m>x</m>-direction, which results in an increase of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> in the <m>y</m>-direction. Therefore, the point on the line with an <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>3</m> is <m>(3, -1 + \frac{2}{3}) = (3, -\frac{1}{3})</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose we decrease <m>x</m> by 3.25 from the point <m>(2,-1)</m>. How does the <m>y</m>-value change? What is the point on the line with <m>x</m>-coordinate <m>-1.25</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            As we decrease <m>x</m> by 3.25 from <m>(2, -1)</m>, the <m>y</m>-value decreases by <m>\frac{13}{6}</m>. The point on the line with the <m>x</m>-coordinate <m>-1.25</m> is <m>(-1.25, -\frac{19}{6})</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            If we decrease <m>x</m> by <m>3.25</m> from the point <m>(2, -1)</m> the <m>y</m>-value will change by <m>-3.25 (\frac{2}{3}) = -\frac{13}{6}</m>. Therefore, the point on the line with an <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>-1.25</m> is <m>(-1.25, -1 + -\frac{13}{6}) = (-1.25, -\frac{19}{6})</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Now, suppose we increase <m>x</m> by some arbitrary value <m>3t</m> from the point <m>(2,-1)</m>. How does the <m>y</m>-value change? What is the point on the line with <m>x</m>-coordinate <m>2+3t</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            If we increase <m>x</m> by an arbitrary value <m>3t</m>, the <m>y</m>-value will change by <m>2t</m>. The point on the line with <m>x</m>-coordinate <m>2 + 3t</m> is <m>(2 + 3t, -1 + 2t)</m>. 
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            If we increase <m>x</m> by some arbitrary value <m>3t</m> from the point <m>(2, -1)</m>, the <m>y</m>-value will change by <m>3t * \frac{2}{3} = 2t</m>. The point on the line with <m>x</m>-coordinate <m>2 + 3t</m> is <m>(2 + 3t, -1 +2t)</m>. 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Remember that the horizontal component of a vector describes the <q>run</q> and the vertical component measures the <q>rise</q> of the vector. So the slope of the line is related to <em>any</em> vector whose <m>y</m>-component divided by the <m>x</m>-component is the slope of the line. For the line in this activity, we might use the vector <m>\langle 3,2 \rangle</m> to describe the direction of the line. Explain why the terminal points of the vectors <m>\vr(t)</m>, where
            <me>
              \vr(t) = \langle 2,-1 \rangle + \langle 3,2 \rangle t,
            </me>
            trace out the graph of the line through the point <m>(2,-1)</m> with slope <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            The terminal point of the vector <m>\langle 2, -1 \rangle</m> is the point <m>(2, -1)</m>. Any vector that is a scalar multiple of <m>\langle 3, 2 \rangle</m> has a slope of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>. If we start at the terminal point of <m>\langle 2, -1</m>, which is the point <m>(2, -1)</m>, and add scalar multiples of the vector <m>\langle 3, 2 \rangle</m>, the terminal point of these scalar vectors will trace out the graph of the line through the point <m>(2, -1)</m> with a slope of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The terminal point of the vector <m>\langle 2, -1 \rangle</m> is the point <m>(2, -1)</m>. Any vector that is a scalar multiple of <m>\langle 3, 2 \rangle</m> has a slope of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>. If we start at the terminal point of <m>\langle 2, -1</m>, which is the point <m>(2, -1)</m>, and add scalar multiples of the vector <m>\langle 3, 2 \rangle</m>, the terminal point of these scalar vectors will trace out the graph of the line through the point <m>(2, -1)</m> with a slope of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Now we extend this vector approach to <m>\R^3</m> and consider a second example. Let <m>\mathcal{L}</m> be the line in <m>\R^3</m> through the point <m>(1,0,2)</m> in the direction of the vector <m>\langle 2, -1, 4 \rangle</m>. Find the coordinates of three distinct points on line <m>\mathcal{L}</m>. Explain your thinking.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Three such points on the line defined by <m>\vr(t) = \langle 1, 0, 2 \rangle + \langle 2, -1, 4 \rangle t</m> are <m>(1, 1, -3), (3, -1, 6)</m> and <m>(5, -2, 10)</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To find any point on the line, plug in any <m>t</m>-value. <m>\vr(-1) = \langle 1, 0, 2 \rangle + (-1) \langle 2, -1, 4 \rangle   = (-1, 1, -2)</m>. <m>\vr(1) = \langle 1, 0, 2 \rangle + 1 \langle 2, -1, 4 \rangle  = (3, -1, 6)</m>. <m>\vr(2) = \langle 1, 0, 2 \rangle + 2\langle 2, -1, 4 \rangle  = (5, -2, 10)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a vector in the form
              <me>
                \vr(t) = \langle x_0, y_0, z_0 \rangle + \langle a,b,c \rangle t
             </me>
             whose terminal points trace out the line <m>\mathcal{L}</m> that is described in (e).  That is, you should be able to locate any point on the line by determining a corresponding value of <m>t</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m> \vr(t) =\langle 1, 0, 2 \rangle + t \langle 2, -1, 4 \rangle  </m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m> \vr(t) =\langle 1, 0, 2 \rangle + t \langle 2, -1, 4 \rangle  </m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
