  <subsection>
    <title>Planes in Space</title>
    <p>
      Now that we have a way of describing lines, we would like to develop a means of describing planes in three dimensions. In <xref ref="S-Precalc-3Dcoord">Section</xref>, we studied the coordinate planes and planes parallel to them. In particular, fundamental planes were of the form <m>coordinate = constant</m>, like <m>x=1, y=-2, \text{or} z=\sqrt{3}</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fundamentalplanewithvector">
      <caption>A plot of <m>x=1</m> in red, <m>y=-2</m> in blue, and <m>z=\sqrt{3}</m> in green with a normal vector plotted for each fundamental plane</caption>
      <interactive title="interactive-fundplanewvect" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate surface="sage">
          from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
          var('t,s')
          plot6=axes(3,1,color="black")+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30)
          plot6+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,sqrt(3)),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),color="green",opacity=.25,frame=False,mesh=True,plot_points=2)
          plot6+=parametric_plot3d((1,t,s),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),color="red",opacity=.25,frame=False,mesh=True,plot_points=2)
          plot6+=parametric_plot3d((s,-2,t),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),frame=False,mesh=True,plot_points=2,color="blue",opacity=.25)
          plot6+=arrow((2,2,sqrt(3)),(2,2,sqrt(3)+1),color="green",width=3)
          plot6+=arrow((1,2,0),(2,2,0),color="red",width=3)
          plot6+=arrow((-0.5,-2,1),(-0.5,-1,1),color="blue",width=3,aspect_ratio=1)
          plot6
        </slate>
      </interactive>
      </figure>
    <p>  
      As shown in <xref ref="fundamentalplanewithvector"/>, any vector in a plane with <m>x= \text{constant}</m> will be orthogonal to the vector <m>\langle 1,0,0 \rangle</m>, any vector in a plane with <m>y= \text{constant}</m> will be orthogonal to the vector <m>\langle 0,1,0 \rangle</m>, and any vector in a plane with <m>z= \text{constant}</m> will be orthogonal to the vector <m>\langle 0,0,1 \rangle</m>. We will use this idea to define a plane in general.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>plane</term><idx><h>plane</h><h>definition</h></idx> <m>p</m> in space is the set of all terminal points of vectors emanating from a given point <m>P_0</m> perpendicular to a fixed vector <m>\vn</m>, as shown in <xref ref="Planewithvector">Figure</xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <figure xml:id="Planewithvector">
      <caption>A plot of a plane with normal vector <m>\vn</m> in red and vector on the plane <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> in orange</caption>
      <interactive title="interactive-Planewithvector" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate surface="sage">
          from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
          var('t,s')
          scale=2
          plot7=axes(3,1,color="black",opacity=0.25)+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30,frame=False)
          plot7+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,-s/2+t/3+1),(s,-3,3),(t,-3,3),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.25,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
          plot7+=arrow((1,1,5/6),(1+(1/2)*scale,1-1/3*scale,5/6+scale),color="red",width=2)
          plot7+=arrow((1,1,5/6),(-1,0,5/3),color="orange",width=2)
          plot7+=point3d((1,1,5/6),color="black",size=50)
          plot7+=text3d("P",(1.3,1.5,0.75),color="black",fontsize=30)
          plot7+=point3d((-1,0,5/3),color="black",size=50)
          plot7+=text3d("Q",(-1.2,0.5,2),color="black",fontsize=30)
          show(plot7,viewpoint=[[-0.0746,-0.4712,-0.8788],164.15],camera_position=[3.2671,9.5358,7.487])
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Like the definition of a line, the definition of a plane given above uses a starting point and a vector as the critical pieces of information. For a line, you begin at the starting point and move as much as you want parallel to the given vector (the direction vector). For a plane, you begin at the starting point and move as much as you want orthogonal to the given vector (the normal vector). For a line, you move only in the direction of the given vector whereas on a plane you cannot move at all in the direction of the given vector.
    </p>
   <!--  <figure xml:id="Planewithvector">
      <caption>A point <m>P_0</m> on a plane <m>p</m> with a normal vector <m>\vn</m></caption>
      <image width="73%" source="images/fig_9_5_plane_normal"/>
    </figure> -->

    <p>
      The definition allows us to find the equation of a plane. Assume that <m>\vn=\langle a,b,c\rangle</m>, <m>P = (x_0, y_0, z_0)</m>, and that <m>Q=(x,y,z)</m> is an arbitrary point on the plane. Since the vector <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> lies in the plane, it must be perpendicular to <m>\vn</m>. This means that
      <md>
        <mrow>0 =\mathstrut \amp  \vn\cdot\overrightarrow{PQ}</mrow>
        <mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \vn\cdot \big(\langle x,y,z \rangle - \langle x_0, y_0,
            z_0\rangle\big)</mrow>
        <mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  \vn \cdot \langle x-x_0, y-y_0, z-z_0 \rangle</mrow>
        <mrow>=\mathstrut \amp  a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0).</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      The fixed vector <m>\vn</m> perpendicular to the plane is frequently called a <em>normal vector</em> to the plane. We may now summarize our new equation for a plane. 
    </p>

    <assemblage xml:id="Plane-scalar-equation">
      <title>Equations of a plane</title>
      <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <em>scalar equation</em> of the plane<idx><h>plane</h><h>scalar equation</h></idx> with normal vector <m>\vn =\langle a,b,c \rangle</m> containing the point <m>P = (x_0, y_0,z_0)</m> is
            <men xml:id="eq_9_5_plane_norm">
              a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0) = 0.
            </men>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The <em>vector equation</em> of the plane<idx><h>plane</h><h>vector equation</h></idx> with normal vector <m>\vn =\langle a,b,c \rangle</m> containing the points <m>P = (x_0, y_0,z_0)</m> and <m>Q = (x,y,z)</m> is
            <men xml:id="eq_9_5_plane_norm_vector">
              \vn \cdot \overrightarrow{PQ} = 0.
            </men>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    </assemblage>
    <p>
      We may take the scalar equation of a plane a little further and note that since
      <me>
        a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0) = 0,
      </me>
      it equivalently follows that
      <me>
        ax + by + cz = ax_0+by_0+cz_0.
      </me>
      That is, we may write an equation of a plane as <m>ax+by+cz = d</m> where <m>d = \vn\cdot\langle x_0,y_0,z_0\rangle</m>.
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        If we would like to describe the plane passing through the point <m>P=(4,-2,1)</m> and perpendicular to the vector <m>\vn = \langle 1, 2, 1 \rangle</m>, we have
        <me>
          \langle 1,2,1 \rangle\cdot \langle x,y,z\rangle = \langle 1,2,1 \rangle\cdot \langle 4,-2,1\rangle
        </me>
        or
        <me>
          x + 2y + z = 1.
        </me>
        Notice that the coefficients of <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m> in this description give a vector perpendicular to the plane. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="exampleplane1">
        <caption>A plot of a plane with normal vector <m>\vn</m> in red and vector on the plane <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> in orange</caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-exampleplane1" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
            var('t,s')
            plot8=axes(3,1,color="black",opacity=0.5)+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30,frame=False)
            plot8+=parametric_plot3d((s,t,1-s-2*t),(s,-2,2),(t,-2,2),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,opacity=0.5,aspect_ratio=1,mesh_opacity=0.25)
            plot8+=arrow((0,0,1),(0+(1),0+2,1+1),color="red",width=2)
            plot8+=text3d("&lt;1,2,1&gt;",(1.2,2.5,2.5),color="red",fontsize=25)
            show(plot8,viewpoint=[[-0.4579,-0.5809,-0.673],124.11],camera_position=[15.3888,4.2661,3.2235])
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        For instance, if we are presented with the plane
        <me>
          -2x + y - 3z = 4,
        </me>
        we know that <m>\vn = \langle -2, 1, -3\rangle</m> is a vector perpendicular to the plane.
      </p>
    </example>
    <activity xml:id="A_9_5_9">
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a scalar equation of the plane <m>p_1</m> passing through the point <m>(0, 2, 4)</m> and perpendicular to the vector <m>\vn=\langle 2, -1, 1\rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>2(x) - (y - 2) + (z - 4) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>2(x - 0) - 1(y - 2) + 1(z - 4) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Is the point <m>(2, 0, 2)</m> on the plane <m>p_1</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            No, the point <m>(2, 0, 2)</m> is not on the plane <m>p_1</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Plug in <m>(2, 0, 2)</m> to the equation of the plane. Does <m>2(2) - (0 - 2) + (2 - 4) = 0</m>? No, so the point is not on the plane <m>p_1</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a scalar equation of the plane <m>p_2</m> that is parallel to <m>p_1</m> and passing through the point <m>(3, 0, 4)</m>. (Hint: Compare normal vectors of the planes.)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>2(x - 3) - 1(y) + (z - 4) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Parallel planes have the same normal vector: <m>2(x - 3) - 1(y) + (z - 4) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a parametric description of the line <m>l</m> passing through the point <m>(2,0,2)</m> and perpendicular to the plane <m>p_3</m> described by the equation <m>x+2y-2z = 7</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>x(t) = 2 + t, y(t) = 2t, z(t) = 2 - 2t</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The normal vector of the plane <m>p_3</m> is <m>\langle 1, 2, -2 \rangle</m>, which will be the direction of line <m>l</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The corresponding parametric equations are <m>x(t) = 2 + t, y(t) = 2t, z(t) = 2 - 2t</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the point at which <m>l</m> intersects the plane <m>p_3</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>(3, 2, 0)</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We need to plug in the parametric equations from <m>d</m> into <m>x + 2y - 2z = 7</m> and solve for <m>t</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>(2 + t) + 2(0 + 2t) - 2(2 - 2t) = 7</m>. Solve to get <m>t = 1</m>. Plug <m>t = 1</m> into the parametric equations to get the point of intersection <m>(3, 2, 0)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
    <example>
      <p>
        Just as two distinct points in space determine a line, three non-collinear points in space determine a plane. Consider three points <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m> in space, not all lying on the same line as shown in <xref ref="exampleplane2">Figure</xref>.
      </p>

      <!-- <figure xml:id="F_9_5_Plane">
        <caption>A plane determined by three points <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m></caption>
        <image width="73%" source="images/fig_9_5_plane_3pts"/>
      </figure> -->
      <figure xml:id="exampleplane2">
        <caption>A plane determined by three points <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m></caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-exampleplane2" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            var('s,t')
            P0=(-1/2,-1/2,0)
            P1=(1/2,-1/2,0)
            P2=(-1/2,1/2,0)
            d=1.5
            plot9=parametric_plot3d((s,-s/3+t,0),(s,-d,d),(t,-d,d),color="green",mesh=True,plot_points=4,frame=False,opacity=0.35)
            plot9+=arrow(P0,P1,color="blue")+arrow(P0,P2,color="blue")+arrow(P0,(-1/2,-1/2,1.5),color="red")
            plot9+=point(P0,size=30,color="black")+point(P1,size=30,color="black")+point(P2,size=30,color="black")
            plot9+=text3d("P\u2080",(-.75,-0.85,0.35),color="black",fontsize=25)+text3d("P\u2081",(1,-0.45,0.35),color="black",fontsize=25)
            plot9+=text3d("P\u2082",(-.75,0.75,0.35),color="black",fontsize=25)
            #+text3d("p",(2.5,2,0),color="green",fontsize=25)
            plot9+=arrow(P0,(1,1,0),color="blue")+text3d("P",(1.1,1.3,0.15),color="black",fontsize=25)+point3d((1,1,0),color="black",size=30)
            plot9+=text3d("n",(-0.5,-0.5,2),color="red",fontsize=25)
            show(plot9,viewpoint=[[-0.8414,-0.2517,-0.4782],64.05],camera_position=[3.2031,-4.8751,4.9657])
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Notice that the vectors <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2}</m> both lie in the plane <m>p</m>. If we form their cross-product
        <me>
          \vn = \overrightarrow{P_0P_1} \times \overrightarrow{P_0P_2},
        </me>
        we obtain a normal vector to the plane <m>p</m>. Therefore, if <m>P</m> is any other point on <m>p</m>, it then follows that <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P}</m> will be perpendicular to <m>\vn</m>, and we have the equation:
        <men xml:id="eq_9_5_plane_vect">
          \vn \cdot \overrightarrow{P_0P} = 0
        </men>
      </p>
    </example>
    <activity xml:id="A_9_5_7">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Let <m>P_0 = (1,2,-1)</m>, <m>P_1 = (1, 0 ,-1)</m>, and <m>P_2 = (0,1,3)</m> and let <m>p</m> be the plane containing <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, and <m>P_2</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine the components of the vectors <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1} = \langle 0, -2, 0 \rangle</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2} = \langle -1, -1, 4 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_1} = \langle (1) - (1), (0) - (2), (-1) - (-1) \rangle = \langle 0, -2, 0 \rangle</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{P_0P_2} = \langle (0) - (1), (1) - (2), (3) - (-1) \rangle = \langle -1, -1, 4 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a normal vector <m>\vn</m> to the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vn = \langle -8, 0, -2 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\vn = \overrightarrow{P_0P_1} \times \overrightarrow{P_0P_2} = ((-2)(4) - (0)(-1))\vi - ((0)(4) - (0)(-1))\vj + ((0)(-1) - (-1)(-2))\vj = \langle -8, 0, -2 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a scalar equation of the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>-8(x - 1) - 2(z + 1) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>-8(x - 1) + 0(y - 2) + -2(z + 1) = -8(x - 1) - 2(z + 1) = 0</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider a second plane, <m>q</m>, with scalar equation <m>-3(x-1) + 4(y+3) + 2(z-5)=0</m>.  Find two different points on plane <m>q</m>, as well as a vector <m>\vm</m> that is normal to <m>q</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vm = \langle -3, 4, 2 \rangle</m>. One point on the plane is <m>(1, -3, 5)</m>. For a second point on plane <m>q</m>, choose any <m>x</m>-coordinate and <m>y</m>-coordinate, and then solve for the corresponding <m>z</m>-coordinate.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            From the scalar equation <m>\vm = \langle -3, 4, 2 \rangle</m> and the point used in the equation is <m>(1, -3, 5)</m>, which is on plane <m>q</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            For a second point on plane <m>q</m>, choose any <m>x</m>-coordinate and <m>y</m>-coordinate, and then solve for the corresponding <m>z</m>-coordinate. One such point with <m>x = 1</m>, and <m>y = -2</m> is <m>(1, -2, 3)</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The angle between two planes is the acute angle between their respective normal vectors.  What is the angle between planes <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>62.232^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The angle between the two planes is equal to the angle between the normal vectors. <m>\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\vn\cdot\vm}{|\vn||\vm|}\right) = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{(-8)(-3) + (0)(4) + (-2)(2)}{|\sqrt{68}||\sqrt{29}|}\right) = 62.23^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>    
    </activity>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          A plane in space is the set of all terminal points of vectors emanating from a given point perpendicular to a fixed vector.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>P_1</m>, <m>P_2</m>, and <m>P_3</m> are non-collinear points in space, the vectors <m>\overrightarrow{P_1P_2}</m> and and <m>\overrightarrow{P_1P_3}</m>  are vectors in the plane and the vector <m>\vn = \overrightarrow{P_1P_2} \times \overrightarrow{P_1P_3}</m> is a normal vector to the plane. So any point <m>P</m> in the plane satisfies the equation <m>\overrightarrow{PP_1} \cdot \vn = 0</m>.  If we let <m>P = (x,y,z)</m>, <m>\vn = \langle a,b,c \rangle</m> be the normal vector, and <m>P_1 = (x_0,y_0,z_0)</m>, we can also represent the plane with the equation
          <me>
            a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0) = 0.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

